  "prompt": "What ever happened to Mad Cow Disease?",
  "response": "Mad Cow Disease, also known as Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE), gained significant attention in the 1990s and early 2000s due to its link to variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD) in humans. vCJD is a rare degenerative brain disorder that is fatal. BSE is believed to be transmitted to humans through the consumption of infected beef products.\n\nSince its peak, the incidence of BSE has drastically declined. This reduction is largely due to several key measures:\n\n1. **Regulatory Actions:** Many countries, especially in Europe and North America, introduced stringent regulations to control BSE. These measures included banning the use of animal by-products in cattle feed, improving surveillance systems to detect BSE, and removing specified risk materials from the food chain.\n\n2. **Increased Awareness and Research:** There has been significant investment in research to better understand BSE, improve diagnosis, and develop guidelines to prevent its spread.\n\n3. **Improved Agricultural Practices:** Enhanced cattle farming practices and biosecurity measures have helped reduce the risk of BSE occurrence.\n\nAs a result of these efforts, the number of BSE cases worldwide has sharply decreased, and it is now considered to be largely under control. However, monitoring and preventive actions continue to ensure food safety and prevent any potential resurgence. It's important to remain vigilant, as the nature of prion diseases, like BSE and vCJD, requires careful and sustained attention to ensure they remain rare.",
